"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49779","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-05-14","<p> </p><p>The Environment Agency defines a “Watercourse” according to section 72(1) of the Land Drainage Act 1991. It includes all rivers and streams and all ditches, drains, cuts, culverts, dikes, sluices, sewers (other than public sewers within the meaning of the Water Industry Act 1991) and passages, through which water flows.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Insurance companies take into account a range of factors in setting policy premiums and excesses, and different insurers take different approaches to assessing flood risk. Certain insurance companies would use proximity to a watercourse to assess the risk of flooding to a property, whilst other companies may use postcodes to assess flood risk or their own flood risk models.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson",,"2014-05-14T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49779/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49779/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49779/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-05-06",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what the Environment Agency classifies as a watercourse; if he will ensure that insurance companies can differentiate between major watercourses and watercourses of no consequence; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Geoffrey Clifton-Brown","The Cotswolds","Geoffrey Clifton-Brown","197871"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49780","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-05-13","<p> </p><p>Our records do not currently distinguish between farms and other claimants; the figure provided relates to all eligible claimants paid (including farms).</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The total value of all Common Agricultural Policy claims paid by the Rural Payments Agency and the Forestry Commission to all claimants with a registered address in Herefordshire during the 5 years up to 15 October 2013 was €261,476,438.25.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-05-13T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49780/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49780/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49780/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-05-06",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what the total value is of Common Agricultural Policy payments to farms in Herefordshire in the last five years for which data are available.","false","Biography information for Jesse Norman","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","197808"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49782","HM Treasury","false","2014-05-13","<p>I have done so today.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2014-05-13T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49782/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49782/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49782/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-05-06",,"1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he intends to answer Question 195074, from the hon. Member for Leicester West, on social care providers and non-payments of the National Minimum Wage.","false","Biography information for Liz Kendall","Leicester West","Liz Kendall","197784"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49783","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-05-13","<p>The Government takes doorstep crime very seriously and the issue has been identified as a top priority by the Consumer Protection Partnership (CPP) which brings together enforcement, consumer education, and advocacy partners to identify, prioritise and coordinate collective action to tackle the issues causing greatest harm to consumers.</p><p> </p><p>Both the National Trading Standards Board (NTSB) and Trading Standards Scotland (TSS), which are funded by BIS, are putting resources into tackling doorstep crime and Trading Standards Officers across the country are cracking down on these fraudsters. In Lincolnshire for example, Trading Standards has teamed up with the Police and Community Lincs to raise awareness of doorstep crime amongst professionals caring for the elderly, including awareness of bogus callers, rogue traders, distraction burglary, and scam mail. To date 330 health and social care professionals who work regularly with 4,300 elderly and vulnerable people have been trained in how to spot potential victims and how to intervene at an early stage of a scam.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Doorstep Crime will also be the focus on this year's National Consumer Week in November 2014, when CPP Partners and the Government will work together to in raise consumer awareness of how to spot a bogus salesperson and where to report it.</p><p> </p><p>We are also hitting the perpetrators of fraud hard. A recent operation involving Trading Standards companies across the country and 20 police forces brought down a trio of fraudsters targeting vulnerable caravan park residents across the country. This resulted in 6 years of custodial sentences being handed down and the recovery of £20,000 in cash.</p><p> </p><p>We encourage anyone who believes that they have been the victim of doorstep crime or fraud to contact the Citizens Advice Consumer helpline on 08454 040506.</p>","Cardiff Central","Jenny Willott",,"2014-05-13T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49783/answer","Biography information for Jenny Willott","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49783/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49783/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-05-06",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to protect consumers from fraud and other doorstep crimes.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Mr Frank Field","197891"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49784","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-05-14","<p /> <p /> <p>DWP have discussed with contractors the payment of the London Living Wage. Telereal Trillium have worked with us so that from April 2014 all of their London based staff were paid at least the level of the living wage. Discussions are continuing with our other major contractor, Cofely.</p><p> </p><p>We intend to have the same negotiations regarding staff based across the regions where the situation is currently:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>REGION</p></td><td><p>NUMBER OF STAFF</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Scotland</p></td><td><p>539</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North East</p></td><td><p>309</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North West</p></td><td><p>885</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Yorks &amp; Humber</p></td><td><p>529</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East Midlands</p></td><td><p>255</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>West Midlands</p></td><td><p>770</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East Of England</p></td><td><p>252</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Wales</p></td><td><p>279</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South East</p></td><td><p>366</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>London</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South West</p></td><td><p>307</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>TOTAL</p></td><td><p>4,493</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>It is not possible to provide further breakdown of these figures as this information is commercially sensitive.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2014-05-14T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49784/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49784/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49784/answer","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49784/answer/previousversion/9759","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-05-06",,"1","House of Commons","To ask